, "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 2, "score_up": 24, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"rumble_embed": "https://rumble.com/embed/v7475na/"}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "text", "uuid": "1ASsZEzBvW", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 18, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "", "id": 8638382, "raw_content": "Since 2023, Washington State has been quietly taking 0.58% of every worker's paycheck for a new mandatory long-term care program called WA Cares.\n\nThe pitch: pay in for 10 years, get $36,500 toward care when you're older.\n\nThe reality:\n\n\u2022 A $300K earner pays 6 times more than a $50K earner. Same $36,500 benefit. No one advertised that.\n\n\u2022 After just 3 years of paying in, you can claim the full $36,500 immediately if you have a qualifying care need. Sounds like a reasonable safety net. Until you see what \"qualifying\" actually means.\n\n\u2022 The care needs assessment can be done over the phone. Per official state documents, it \u201cmay be based on self-report and could be verified by a health professional.\u201d May. Could. No mandatory doctor exam required.\n\n\u2022 What counts as a care need? Needing help with 3 daily activities. And \"someone verbally reminding you to take your medication\" legally qualifies as one of them.\n\nThe tax collection side? Airtight.\n\nThe claims side? A phone call. Self-reported. Assessed by a state staffer.\n\nSources: wacaresfund.wa.gov, SB 5291\n\nNobody would defraud this. Right?", "author": "travelfeet", "created": 1779674043124, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "Calumet57", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "WA Fraud", "last_comment_created": 1779675971157, "content": "<p>Since 2023, Washington State has been quietly taking 0.58% of every worker's paycheck for a new mandatory long-term care program called WA Cares.</p>\n<p>The pitch: pay in for 10 years, get $36,500 toward care when you're older.</p>\n<p>The reality:</p>\n<p>\u2022 A $300K earner pays 6 times more than a $50K earner. Same $36,500 benefit. No one advertised that.</p>\n<p>\u2022 After just 3 years of paying in, you can claim the full $36,500 immediately if you have a qualifying care need. Sounds like a reasonable safety net. Until you see what &quot;qualifying&quot; actually means.</p>\n<p>\u2022 The care needs assessment can be done over the phone. Per official state documents, it \u201cmay be based on self-report and could be verified by a health professional.\u201d May. Could. No mandatory doctor exam required.</p>\n<p>\u2022 What counts as a care need? Needing help with 3 daily activities. And &quot;someone verbally reminding you to take your medication&quot; legally qualifies as one of them.</p>\n<p>The tax collection side? Airtight.</p>\n<p>The claims side? A phone call. Self-reported. Assessed by a state staffer.</p>\n<p>Sources: wacaresfund.wa.gov, SB 5291</p>\n<p>Nobody would defraud this. Right?</p>\n", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 1, "score_up": 18, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "link", "uuid": "1ASsZEydZ2", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 32, "suggested_sort": 0, "pos